            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Raj Miller\u2019s name tells a story before he even speaks. Born in Daly City to an Indian mother from Mumbai and a white American father from Ohio, his childhood was a vibrant fusion of cultures. The family home was filled with the scent of his mother\u2019s intricate curries and the sound of his father\u2019s classic rock records. It was in that kitchen, watching his mother toast spices, that Raj found his calling. The precise, alchemical process of creating flavor fascinated him more than any textbook.\n\nAfter high school, he enrolled in the Culinary Arts program at City College of San Francisco, but the structured curriculum felt stifling. The real education, he realized, was in the city\u2019s demanding kitchens. He dropped out after three semesters for a grueling prep cook position at a revered Financial District restaurant. For fifteen years, he worked his way up the line\u2014enduring burns, 16-hour days, and the relentless pressure of service.\n\nThe major turning point came when he was 38. He and his most trusted sous chef, Maria Flores, pooled their life savings and took a massive risk, securing a loan to take over a failing space in Hayes Valley. They named their restaurant \"Mela,\" the Sanskrit word for a gathering or fair. It was a reflection of Raj\u2019s heritage, offering Californian cuisine with a refined, contemporary Indian influence.\n\nToday, Raj is the Executive Chef and a proud partner at Mela. His daily routine is a ritual: an early Muni ride from his apartment in the Mission to the restaurant, followed by meetings with suppliers and hours of intense prep with his team. His personal life is quiet; a decade-old amicable divorce left him married to his work. His staff is his family, and the restaurant is his home. Though he earns a comfortable living, the pressure is constant. His quiet dream is to earn a Michelin star\u2014not for the ego, but as the ultimate validation for a life spent honoring the flavors his mother first introduced him to, a testament to his unique San Franciscan story."
