            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers standing on a stool in the Daly City kitchen, his head barely clearing the stovetop. His mother swirled ghee in a hot pan, and with a flick of her wrist, sent mustard seeds skittering across the surface. They popped and crackled, a tiny, fragrant firework show. It wasn\u2019t just cooking; it was alchemy. That sound was the first note of a symphony he knew, even at eight years old, that he had to learn to conduct. It was the moment an obsession was born.\n\n2.\nThe sizzle of his own forearm on the flat-top was louder than the head chef\u2019s screaming. He was 22, buried deep in a brutal Saturday night service. The searing pain and the shame of the mistake made him want to walk out forever. Instead, he ran his arm under cold water, wrapped it tightly in gauze, and stepped back to the line. In that moment, enduring the sting with every plated dish, he learned that resilience was a more valuable ingredient than anything in the pantry.\n\n3.\nThe day before Mela opened, he and Maria stood on the Hayes Valley sidewalk with a stencil and a can of gold paint. As he carefully filled in the letters, the weight of the loan felt crushing. But then Maria caught his eye and grinned, a smudge of paint on her cheek. In that shared, terrified smile, the fear transformed into pure, electrifying purpose. This wasn't just a restaurant anymore; it was theirs. It was a declaration of everything they had sacrificed.\n\n4.\nA few years after opening Mela, he came home to his Mission apartment after his ex-wife had moved out the last of her things. The silence was vast and unnerving. He couldn\u2019t stand it, so he walked back to the restaurant. Sitting alone in the dark dining room, the faint scent of cardamom and cooled steel felt more like home than his empty apartment ever could. He realized then the restaurant wasn't just his work; it was the new partnership that demanded all of him.\n\n5.\nAn elderly woman stopped him after a flawless Friday service, her eyes glistening. \"Your food,\" she said, her voice trembling slightly, \"it tastes like a memory I didn't know I had.\" The comment struck him deeper than any critic\u2019s praise. In that moment, the vague ambition for a Michelin star became sharp and clear. It wasn\u2019t about ego. It was for that feeling\u2014the ultimate proof that his mother's legacy, filtered through him, could become a part of someone else's story."
